The [`Snackbar` component](https://github.com/mui-org/material-ui/blob/v4.4.3/packages/material-ui/src/Snackbar/Snackbar.js#L230) handles open/close state, transitions, and positioning, but `Snackbar` delegates control of the look of the `Snackbar` (e.g. background color, typography, padding) to the [`SnackbarContent` component](https://github.com/mui-org/material-ui/blob/v4.4.3/packages/material-ui/src/SnackbarContent/SnackbarContent.js#L48).

If you look at the [Customized snackbars demo](https://material-ui.com/components/snackbars/#customized-snackbars), you&#39;ll see that it changes the background color by specifying a `className` on the `SnackbarContent` element rather than on the `Snackbar` element. You can also achieve the same effect by specifying the `className` within the `ContentProps`. 

The example below demonstrates both approaches for specifying the class name for the content.

```
import React from &quot;react&quot;;
import ReactDOM from &quot;react-dom&quot;;

import Snackbar from &quot;@material-ui/core/Snackbar&quot;;
import SnackbarContent from &quot;@material-ui/core/SnackbarContent&quot;;
import { withStyles } from &quot;@material-ui/core/styles&quot;;
const styles = {
  snackbarStyleViaContentProps: {
    backgroundColor: &quot;orange&quot;
  },
  snackbarStyleViaNestedContent: {
    backgroundColor: &quot;lightgreen&quot;,
    color: &quot;black&quot;
  }
};
function App({ classes }) {
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;Snackbar
        anchorOrigin={{
          vertical: &quot;top&quot;,
          horizontal: &quot;right&quot;
        }}
        open={true}
        ContentProps={{
          &quot;aria-describedby&quot;: &quot;message-id&quot;,
          className: classes.snackbarStyleViaContentProps
        }}
        message={
          &lt;span id=&quot;message-id&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div&gt;Hi there! Some message.&lt;/div&gt;
          &lt;/span&gt;
        }
      /&gt;
      &lt;Snackbar
